# Abstract

Although variation in effect sizes and predicted values among studies of similar phenomena is inevitable, there is evidence that such variation may far exceed what might be produced by sampling error. One possible explanation for variation among results is differences among researchers in the decisions they make regarding statistical analyses. A growing array of articles explore this in different (mostly social science) fields, showing that, despite having the same data and research question, results differ substantially between analysts. We implement an analogous study in ecology and evolutionary biology, a field in which there has been no empirical exploration of the variation in effect sizes or model predictions of dependent variables generated by the analytical decisions of different researchers. Using two unpublished datasets, one from conservation ecology (Eucalyptus seedling recruitment) and one from evolutionary ecology (Blue Tit growth), and recruited 145 analyst teams, comprising 206 analysts to investigate the answer to our prespecified research questions. They produced 174 analyses of the Blue Tit dataset, and 128 analyses of the Eucalyptus dataset. We were interested in how much the mean effect size, and model predictions differed between analyses as well as how much of this variation is explained by peer reviewed analysis quality, uniqueness of variable selection, and inclusion of random effects. We found more variation in results for the Blue Tit dataset than the Eucalyptus dataset, though variation was substantial in both with some analyses showing significant positive and negative effects, and others finding no significant signal in the data. We also found substantial variation in the variable selection, reviewer ratings and random effects structures between analyses, but we found no strong relationship between any of these and variation from the meta-analytic mean, i.e. analyses with results that were dissimilar from others were no more or less likely to have unique variable sets, receive poor reviews or use random effects in their models than those analyses that found results that were similar to others.

# Introduction

One value of science derives from its production of replicable, and thus reliable, results. When we repeat a study using the original methods we should be able to expect a similar result. However, perfect replicability is not a reasonable goal. Effect sizes will vary, and even reverse in sign, by chance alone \@ref(gelman2009). However, observed patterns can differ for other reasons as well. It could be that we do not sufficiently understand the conditions that led to the original result so when we seek to replicate it, the conditions differ due to some 'hidden moderator'. This hidden moderator hypothesis is described by meta-analysts in ecology and evolutionary biology as 'true biological heterogeneity' \@ref(senior2016). This idea of true heterogeneity is popular in ecology and evolutionary biology, and there are good reasons to expect it to be true in the complex systems in which we work \@ref(shavit2017). However, despite similar expectations in psychology, recent evidence in that discipline contradicts the hypothesis that moderators are common obstacles to replicability, as variability in results in a large 'many labs' collaboration was largely unrelated to commonly hypothesized moderators such as the conditions under which the studies were administered \@ref(klein2018). Another possible explanation for variation in effect sizes is that researchers often present biased samples of results, thus reducing the likelihood that later studies will produce similar effect sizes \@ref(open2015, parker2016, forstmeier2017, fraser2018). It also may be that although researchers did successfully replicate the conditions, the experiment, and measured variables, analytical decisions differed sufficiently among studies to create divergent results \@ref(simonsohn2015, silberzahn2018).

Analytical decisions vary among studies because researchers have many options. Researchers need to decide how to exclude possibly anomalous or unreliable data, how to construct variables, which variables to include in their models, and which statistical methods to use. Depending on the data set, this short list of choices could encompass thousands or millions of possible alternative specifications \@ref(simonsohn2015). However, researchers making these decisions presumably do so with the goal of doing the best possible analysis, or at least the best analysis within their current skill set. Thus it seems likely that some specification options are more probable than others, possibly because they have previously been shown (or claimed) to be better, or because they are more well known. Of course, some of these different analyses (maybe many of them) may be equally valid alternatives. Regardless, on probably any topic in ecology and evolutionary biology, we can encounter differences in choices of data analysis. The extent of these differences in analyses and the degree to which these differences influence the outcomes of analyses and therefore studies' conclusions are important empirical questions. These questions are especially important given that many papers draw conclusions after applying a single method, or even a single statistical model, to analyze a data set.

The possibility that different analytical choices could lead to different outcomes has long been recognized, and various efforts to address this possibility have been pursued in the literature. For instance, one common method in ecology and evolutionary biology involves creating a set of candidate models, each consisting of a different (though often similar) set of predictor variables, and then, for the predictor variable of interest, averaging the slope across all models (i.e. model averaging) \@ref(burnham2002, grueber2011). This method reduces the chance that a conclusion is contingent upon a single model specification, though use and interpretation of this method is not without challenges [@grueber2011]. Further, the models compared to each other typically differ only in the inclusion or exclusion of certain predictor variables and not in other important ways, such as methods of parameter estimation. More explicit examination of outcomes of differences in model structure, model type, data exclusion, or other analytical choices can be implemented through sensitivity analyses \@ref(e.g., noble2017). Sensitivity analyses, however, are typically rather narrow in scope, and are designed to assess the sensitivity of analytical outcomes to a particular analytical choice rather than to a large universe of choices. Recently, however, analysts in the social sciences have proposed extremely thorough sensitivity analysis, termed 'multiverse analysis' [@steegen2016] or the 'specification curve' \@ref(simonsohn2015), as a means of increasing the reliability of results. With these methods, researchers identify relevant decision points encountered during analysis and conduct the analysis many times to incorporate all plausible decisions made at each of these points. The study's conclusions are then based on a broad set of the possible analyses and so allow the analyst to distinguish between robust conclusions and those that are highly contingent on particular model specifications. These are useful outcomes, but specifying a universe of possible modelling decisions is not a trivial undertaking. Further, the analyst's knowledge and biases will influence decisions about the boundaries of that universe, and so there will always be room for disagreement among analysts about what to include. Including more specifications is not necessarily better. Some analytical decisions are better justified than others, and including biologically implausible specifications may undermine this process. Regardless, these powerful methods have yet to be adopted, and even more limited forms of sensitivity analyses are not particularly widespread. Most studies publish a small set of analyses and so the existing literature does not provide much insight into the degree to which published results are contingent on analytical decisions.

Despite the potential major impacts of analytical decisions on variance in results, the outcomes of different individuals' data analysis choices have received limited empirical attention. The only formal exploration of this that we are aware of were (1) an analysis in social science that asked whether male professional football (soccer) players with darker skin tone were more likely to be issued red cards (ejection from the game for rule violation) than players with lighter skin tone \@ref(silberzahn2018) and (2) an analysis in neuroimaging which evaluated nine separate hypotheses involving the neurological responses detected with fMRI in 108 participants divided between two treatments in a decision making task \@ref(botvinik-nezer2020).

In the red card study, twenty-nine teams designed and implemented analyses of a data set provided by the study coordinators \@ref(silberzahn2018). Analyses were peer-reviewed (results blind) by at least two other participating analysts; a level of scrutiny consistent with standard pre-publication peer-review. Among the final 29 analyses, odds-ratios varied from 0.89 to 2.93, meaning point estimates varied from having players with lighter skin tones receive more red cards (odds ratio \< 1) to a strong effect of players with darker skin tones receiving more red cards (odds ratio \> 1). Twenty of the 29 teams found a statistically-significant effect in the predicted direction of players with darker skin tones being issued more red cards. This degree of variation in peer-reviewed analyses from identical data is striking, but the generality of this finding has only just begun to be formally investigated.

In the neuroimaging study, 70 teams evaluated each of the nine different hypotheses with the available fMRI data \@ref(botvinik-nezer2019). These 70 analysts followed a divergent set of workflows that produced a wide range of results. The rate of reporting of statistically significant support for the nine hypotheses ranged from 21% to 84%, and for each hypothesis on average, 20% of research teams observed effects that differed substantially from the majority of other teams. Some of the variability in results among studies could be explained by analytical decisions such as choice of software package, smoothing function, and parametric versus non-parametric corrections for multiple comparisons. However, substantial variability among analyses remained unexplained, and presumably emerged from the many different decisions each analyst made in their long workflows. Such variability in results among analyses from this data set and from the very different red-card data set suggests that sensitivity of analytical outcome to analytical choices may characterize many distinct fields.

To further develop the empirical understanding of the effects of analytical decisions on study outcomes, we chose to estimate the extent to which researchers' data analysis choices drive differences in effect sizes, model predictions, and qualitative conclusions in ecology and evolutionary biology. This is an important extension of the meta-research agenda of evaluating factors influencing replicability in ecology, evolutionary biology, and beyond \@ref(fidler2017). To examine the effects of analytical decisions, we have two different data sets and we will recruit researchers to analyze one or the other of these data sets to answer a question we have defined. The first question is "To what extent is the growth of nestling blue tits (Cyanistes caeruleus) influenced by competition with siblings?" To answer this question, we have a data set that includes brood size manipulations from 332 broods conducted over three years at Wytham Wood, UK. The second question is "How does grass cover influence Eucalyptus spp. seedling recruitment?" For this question, analysts will use a data set that includes, among other variables, number of seedlings in different size classes, percentage cover of different life forms, tree canopy cover, and distance from canopy edge from 351 quadrats spread among 18 sites in Victoria, Australia.

We will explore the impacts of data analysts' choices with descriptive statistics and with a series of tests to attempt to explain the variation among effect sizes and predicted values of the dependent variable produced by the different analysis teams for both data sets separately. To describe the variability, we will present forest plots of the standardized effect sizes and predicted values produced by each of the analysis teams, estimate heterogeneity (both absolute $\tau^2$ and proportional $I^2$) in effect size and predicted values among the results produced by these different teams, and calculate a similarity index that quantifies variability among the predictor variables selected for the different statistical models constructed by the different analysis teams. These descriptive statistics will provide the first estimates of the extent to which explanatory statistical models and their outcomes in ecology and evolutionary biology vary based on the decisions of different data analysts. We will then quantify the degree to which the variability in effect size and predicted values can be explained by (1) variation in the quality of analyses as rated by peer reviewers and (2) the similarity of the choices of predictor variables between individual analyses.

# Methods

The overall structure of the many-analyst study comprises a lead-team who facilitate independent researchers to conduct the analyses and who collate, and meta-analyse and write up the results of the analyses ( [[multi-analyst approaches]] for an overview.)

The overall process consisted of a series of 6 steps: 1. Identifying datasets for analysis, 2. Recruiting independent groups of scientists 3. Independent analysis of the datasets from (1) by groups of researchers (2) 4. Randomised peer-review of submitted methods by (3) 5. Evaluation of variation in effects among different analyses (3) by the lead-team.

## **Step 1: Select Datasets**

We obtained two previously unpublished datasets, one from ecology and conservation (<https://osf.io/t76uy/>), the other from evolutionary ecology (<https://osf.io/34fzc/>). Researchers chose to analyse one or both datasets as they wished, and were provided the corresponding dataset, a description of the methods used to generate that dataset and an accompanying research question.

**Evolutionary ecology**

Our evolutionary ecology data set is relevant to a sub-discipline of life-history research which focuses on identifying costs and trade-offs associated with different phenotypic conditions. These data were derived from a brood-size manipulation experiment imposed on wild birds nesting in boxes provided by researchers in an intensively studied population. Understanding how the growth of nestlings is influenced by the numbers of siblings in the nest can give researchers insights into factors such as the evolution of clutch size, determination of provisioning rates by parents, and optimal levels of sibling competition (Vander Werf 1992, DeKogel 1997, Royle et al. 1999, Verhulst et al. 2006, Nicolaus et al. 2009).

Analysts were provided this data set and instructed to answer the following question: "To what extent is the growth of nestling blue tits (Cyanistes caeruleus) influenced by competition with siblings?"

*Description of data collection*

Researchers conducted brood size manipulations and population monitoring of blue tits (Cyanistes caeruleus) at Wytham Wood, a 380 ha woodland in Oxfordshire, U.K (1o 20'W, 51o 47'N). Researchers regularly checked approximately 1100 artificial nest boxes at the site and monitored the 330 to 450 blue tit pairs occupying those boxes in 2001-2003 during the experiments. Nearly all birds made only one breeding attempt during the April to June study period in a given year. At each blue tit nest, researchers recorded the date the first egg appeared, clutch size, and hatching date. For all chicks alive at age 14 days, researchers measured mass and tarsus length and fitted a uniquely numbered, British Trust for Ornithology (BTO) aluminium leg ring. Researchers attempted to capture all adults at their nests between day 6 and day 14 of the chick-rearing period. For these captured adults, researchers measured mass, tarsus length, and wing length and fitted a uniquely numbered BTO (British Trust for Ornithology) leg ring. During the 2001-2003 breeding seasons, researchers manipulated brood sizes using cross fostering. They matched broods for hatching date and brood size and moved chicks between these paired nests one or two days after hatching. They sought to either enlarge or reduce all manipulated broods by approximately one fourth. To control for effects of being moved, each reduced brood had a portion of its brood replaced by chicks from the paired increased brood, and vice versa. Net manipulations varied from plus or minus four chicks in broods of 12 to 16 to plus or minus one chick in broods of 4 or 5. Researchers left approximately one third of all broods unmanipulated. These unmanipulated broods were not selected systematically to match manipulated broods in clutch size or laying date. There is mass and tarsus length data from 3720 individual chicks divided among 167 experimentally enlarged broods, 165 experimentally reduced broods, and 120 unmanipulated broods. The full list of variables included in the data set is available in Table S1 in the supplementary materials.

**Ecology and conservation**

Our ecology and conservation data set is relevant to a sub-discipline of conservation research which focuses on investigating how best to revegetate private land in agricultural landscapes. These data were collected on private land under the Bush Returns program, an incentive system where participants entered into a contract with the Goulburn Broken Catchment Management Authority and received annual payments if they executed predetermined restoration activities. This particular data set is based on a passive regeneration initiative, where livestock grazing was removed from the property in the hopes that the Eucalyptus spp. overstorey would regenerate without active (and expensive) planting. Analyses of some related data have been published (Miles 2008, Vesk et al. 2016) but those analyses do not address the question analysts answered in our study.

Analysts were provided this dataset and instructed to answer the following question: "How does grass cover influence Eucalyptus spp. seedling recruitment?"

*Description of data collection*

Researchers conducted three rounds of surveys at 18 sites across the Goulburn Broken catchment in northern Victoria, Australia in winter and spring 2006 and autumn 2007. In each survey period, a different set of 15 x 15 m quadrats were randomly allocated across each site within 60 m of existing tree canopies. The number of quadrats at each site depended on the size of the site, ranging from four at smaller sites to 11 at larger sites. The total number of quadrats surveyed across all sites and seasons was 351. The number of Eucalytpus spp. seedlings was recorded in each quadrat along with information on the GPS location, aspect, tree canopy cover, distance to tree canopy, and position in the landscape. Ground layer plant species composition was recorded in three 0.5 x 0.5 m sub-quadrats within each quadrat. Subjective cover estimates of each species as well as bare ground, litter, rock and moss/lichen/soil crusts were recorded. Subsequently, this was augmented with information about the precipitation and solar radiation at each GPS location.

## **Step 2: Recruitment and Initial Survey of Analysts**

The lead team (TP, HF, SN, EG, SG, PV, FF) created a publicly available document providing a general description of the project (osf.io/mn5aj/). The project was advertised at conferences, via Twitter, mailing lists for ecological societies (e.g. Ecolog, Evoldir, Environmental Decisions Group and Transparency in Ecology and Evolution), and via word of mouth. Recruitment aimed to target the population of active ecology, conservation, and evolutionary biology researchers who at minimum had a graduate degree (or were currently studying in a graduate degree) in a relevant discipline. Researchers chose to work either independently or in small teams, each referred to as 'analysis teams' for the sake of simplicity, even though some comprised of only a single individual. We aimed for a minimum of 12 analysis teams to independently analyse each dataset (See Appendix X.1 for sample size justification).

Simultaneously and using the same channels, we recruited volunteers to peer-review the analyses submitted by the other volunteers. Each peer-reviewer was asked to review a minimum of four analyses, with some analysts also serving as reviewers after they had completed their analyses, though they were precluded from reviewing analyses of the same dataset they analysed.

All analysts and reviewers shared in co-authorship on this manuscript and participated in a collaborative process of producing the final manuscript. All analysts signed a consent (ethics) form (<https://osf.io/xyp68/>) approved by the Whitman College Institutional Review Board prior to participation in this study.

## **Step 3: Primary Data Analyses**

Analysis teams registered and answered a demographic and expertise survey ( <https://osf.io/seqzy/>). Analysis teams were provided with the dataset of their choice, and requested to answer specific, accompanying research questions (as outlined in step 1). Following completion and submission of their analyses, analysis teams answered structured surveys eliciting information about their analytical choices, quantitative results and a statement describing their conclusions. All teams were asked to upload their analysis files, including the dataset as it was formatted for analysis, their analysis code (if applicable) and a detailed journal-ready statistical methods section.

::: boxBorder
**Preregistration Deviation:**

We originally planned to have a single survey for analysts to fill in (<https://osf.io/neyc7/>). We had anticipated that each analyst team would produce one model to analyse the research question, however many teams analysed the data through several models so we had to ask them to fill in a new survey (*link to second survey on OSF as well as materials provided*) to adequately collect the data we needed to evaluate heterogenity of results (step 5).
:::

We elicited two main outcomes of interest from the analysts with which to evaluate variation among analyses:

-   Signed effect sizes, elicited as correlation coefficients, describing the strength of a relationship based on the amount of variation in a dependent variable explained by variation in an independent variable.
-   out-of-sample predicted values, or $y$, and can be derived from any explanatory model the analysts could generate from these datasets. Evaluating variation in $y$ facilitates examining differences in the shape of the relationship between the dependent and independent variables and is compatible with some kinds of ecological modelling that are not suited to analysis of signed effect sizes. We elicited three point estimates (predicted values, $y_{25}$, $y_{50}$, $y_{75}$) for the dependent variable of interest for each of three values of the primary independent variable (the 25th percentile, the median, the 75th percentile), setting the values of any co-variates at the corresponding quartiles (25th percentile, median, 75th percentile). We used the 25th and 75th percentiles rather than minimum and maximum values to reduce the chance of occupying unrealistic parameter space. For both the ecology and evolutionary biology datasets we provided corresponding datasets (<https://osf.io/jh7g5>, <https://osf.io/86akx>) to the analysts, as described, that they could substitute into their models to generate out of sample predictions or $y_i$ (see <https://osf.io/dfvym> and <https://osf.io/kr2g9> for materials provided to analysts for this task).

## **Step 4: Peer Reviews of Analyses**

Reviewers were randomly assigned methods sections to peer-review from at least four analysis teams. Each reviewer registered and answered the same demographic and expertise survey provided to the analysts, with the only variation being the ommision of the 'team name' since reviewers worked as individuals, not in teams. Reviewers evaluated the methods section of their assigned analyses in a systematically assigned sequence such that each analysis is allocated to each position in the review sequence for at least one reviewer. For instance,if each reviewer is assigned four analyses to review, then each analysis will be the first analysis assigned to at least one reviewer, the second analysis assigned to another reviewer, the third analysis assigned to yet another reviewer, and the fourth analysis assigned to a fourth reviewer. Balancing the order in which reviewers see the analyses controls for order effects, e.g. a reviewer might be less critical of the first methods section they read than the last. We aimed to obtain at least four reviews of each dataset, and operationalised this by aiming to recruit as many reviewers as there were methods sections to review (or more), and using the qualtrics randomisation functions to ensure that each analysis was assigned to the same number of reviewers. Variation in the number of reviews per analysis is explained by analyses being assigned to reviewers who did not complete their reviews.

Individual reviewers abided by the following process: The reviewer received a description of the methods for a single analysis, which included the narrative methods section, the analysis teams' answers to our survey questions regarding their methods, analysis code (if applicable) and final dataset used in the submitted analysis.

In an online survey (<https://osf.io/4t36u/>), the reviewer was asked to rate the assigned analysis on a continuous numeric scale from 0 - 100 based on the following prompt: "Rate the overall appropriateness of this analysis to answer the research question (one of the two research questions inserted here ) with the available data." We provided additional instructions with which to help the reviewer calibrate their numerical ratings (Appendix X.2)

After providing the numeric rating of the analysis, peer-reviewers were presented with a second prompt in multiple-choice format: "Would the analytical methods presented produce an analysis that is (a) publishable as is, (b) publishable with minor revision, (c) publishable with major revision, (d) deeply flawed and unpublishable?". We also provided the reviewer with a series of prompts asking them to explain their ratings of the analysis and evaluate the choice of statistical analysis type, the process of variable choice and structure of the statistical model, the suitability of variable selection included or excluded from the statistical model, the suitability of the statistical model, dataset subsetting choices, data transformation (or lack of) choices (See appendix X.2).

::: boxBorder
**Preregistration Deviation**:

We provided reviewers with a chance to revisit and update their reviews after they had reviewed all four analyses. We had planned to retain their old and new ratings separately but instead the updated reviews over-wrote the original ones.
:::

## **Step 5: Evaluate Variation**

The lead-team evaluated the variation in methods and results produced by analyst teams, separately for the ecology and conservation and evolutionary ecology datasets. We described the variation in model specification by calculating summary statistics describing the mean, SD and range of the number of variables per model as fixed effects, the number of interaction terms, the number of random effects, as well as the mean, SD and range of sample sizes. We also calculated the number of analyses in which each variable was included.

We used random effects meta-analyses to summarise the variability in the two main outcomes of interest: standardised effect sizes and out-of-sample preductions.

### Response Variables

*Standardised effect size preparation*

The lead team derived standardised effect sizes from each individual analysis. For all effect sizes generated by linear or generalised linear models this was achieved by converting the $t$ value as well as the degrees of freedom $df$ associated with the regression coefficients (e.g. the effect of the number of siblings (predictor) on growth (response) *or* the effect of grass cover (predictor) on seedling recruitment (response) to the correlation coefficient), $r$ using the following equation:

$$
r=\sqrt{\frac{{t}^2}{{t}^2}+df}
$$

This formula can only be applied if $t$ and $df$ values originate from linear or generalized linear models (GLMs; Nakagawa and Cuthill 2007). If linear mixed-effects models (LMMs) or generalized linear mixed-effects models (GLMMs) were used in a given analysis, the exact $df$ is unable to be estimated. Instead, the *adjusted* $df$ can be estimated using the Satterthwaite approximation of $df$, $df_S$, for example. This approximation is automatically generated for LMMs and GLMMs by some programming languages, such as SAS (Luke 2017). However, for analyses using either LMMs or GLMMs that do not produce $df_S$, we obtained $df_S$ by rerunning the same (G)LMMs using the *lmer* or *glmer* function using the *lmerTest* package in R \@ref(kuznetsova2017). We used the $t$ value and substituted $df_S$ for $df$ to obtain the correlation coefficient, $r$. All correlation coefficients $r$ and their accompanying degrees of freedom ($df$, $df_S$) were converted to Fisher's standardized correlation coefficients, $Zr$, and its sampling variance $1/(n-3)$, where $n = df+1$.

*Standardized out of sample predictions* All out of sample predictions for each percentile scenario $y_i$ were elicited on the link scale (see <https://osf.io/dfvym> and <https://osf.io/kr2g9> for materials provided to analysts for this task), consequently we transformed them to the original response scale, along with their standard errors (SE). We used the delta method (Ver Hoef 2012) for the transformation of SE. Further, because we expect some analysts to choose different dependent variables, after transforming values to the original scales, we will then standardize all values as z scores ('standard scores') to put all dependent variables on the same scale and thus make them comparable. This involves taking each relevant value on the original scale (whether a predicted point estimate or a SE associated with that estimate) and subtracting the value in question from the mean value of that dependent variable derived from the full data set and then dividing this difference by the standard deviation, SD, corresponding to the mean from the full data set. Thus all values will be from a distribution with the mean of 0 and SD of 1. We will use the square of the SE associated with predicted values as the sampling variance in the meta-analyses described below, and we will analyze these predicted values in exactly the same ways as we analyze $Zr$ in the following analyses.

::: boxBorder

We were unable to standardize the response variable for the Eucalyptus (ecology and conservation) data was zero inflated and the transformations produced incongruous data. However, all analyses of the Eucalyptus dataset used response variables that provided answers in 'number of Eucalyptus stems per quadrat' so we present the out of sample predictions for the Eucalyptus dataset on an untransformed scale.
:::

### Evaluating Analytic Heterogeneity with Meta-analysis

Both effect size estimates $Zr$ and predicted values of the dependent variable $y_i$ were included in random effects meta-analyses (Higgins et al. 2003, Borenstein et al. 2017) using the *metafor* package in R [@metafor]:

$$
Zr ~ 1 + (1| analysis_identity)
$$

$$  
y_i ~ 1 + (1| analysis_identity)
$$ where $y_i$ is the predicted for the dependent variable at the 25th percentile ($y_{25}$), median ($y_{50}$, or 75th percentile $y_{75}$ of the independent variables. The goal of the meta-analysis is to visualise and quantify the degree of variation among analyses in effect size estimates (Nakagawa and Cuthill 2007), not to test for statistical significance.

The individual $Zr$ effect sizes were weighted with the inverse of sampling variance for $Zr$, whereas the individual predicted values for dependent variable (y) will be weighted by the associated ${SE}^2$. These analyses provide a meta-analytic mean or average $Zr$ and $y_i$ with corresponding 95% confidence intervals. We also derived two types of heterogeneity indices from these meta-analytic models $\tau^2$ and $I^2$, where the $\tau^2$ is the absolute measure of heterogeneity or the between-study variance (in our case, between-team variance) and $I^2$ is a relative measure of heterogeneity obtained by dividing the between-analysis variance (INSERT term) by the sum of between-analysis and within-analysis variance (sampling error variance). $I^2$ is thus the proportion of variance that is due to analytic heterogeneity as opposed to sampling error. When calculating $I^2$, within-study variance is amalgamated across studies to create a "typical" within-study variance which serves as the sampling error variance (Higgins et al. 2003, Borenstein et al. 2017).

For both the ecology and evolutionary biology analyses, we plotted the effect size estimate $Zr$ and predicted values of the dependent variable $y_i$ and their corresponding 95% confidence intervals as well the corresponding meta-analytic means in forest plots to visualise the range, precision and sign of the effect sizes and predicted values.

::: boxBorder
**Preregistration Deviation:**

We did not anticipate analysis teams submitting more than one analysis, consequently we pre-registered the meta-analytic models as having only a single random effect for `analysis_identity`, rather than the nested random effect structure, described above in equations X and Y.

### Explaining Deviation from the Meta-analytic Mean

Finally we assessed the extent to which deviations of the individual effect sizes ($Zr$) or the predicted values of the dependent variable ($y$) from the meta-analytic mean are explained by:

1.  the peer-rating of each analysis team's method section,
2.  a measurement of the 'uniqueness' of the set of predictor variables included in each analysis, and
3.  the choice of whether or not to include random effects in the model.

**Calculating Deviation Scores**

For each analysis we calculated the *deviation score*, or the absolute value of the difference between the meta-analytic mean $Zr$ (or $y$) and the individual $Zr$ or $y$ estimate for each analysis. We Box-Cox transformed the absolute values of the deviation scores to achieve an approximately normal distribution (c.f. Fanelli and Ioannidis 2013, Fanelli et al. 2017). Box-Cox transformed deviations cores served as the dependent variable in a series of general linear mixed models (GLMMs).

**Explaining Variation in Deviation Scores**

We described variation in this dependent variable using a series of univariate analyses, and a multivariate analysis, specified as general linear mixed models (GLMMs). These analyses are secondary to our estimation of variation in effect sizes using meta-analysis and aim to quantify relationships among potential predictors of deviation from the meta-analytic mean, but we had no a priori expectation of effect size and do not make dichotomous decisions about statistical significance.

*Deviation Scores as explained by Reviewer Ratings*

We used the *lme4* package in R (Bates et al. 2015) to fit our GLMMs. When modelling the extent to which numeric reviewer ratings (on a scale from 0 to 100) explain deviation from the average effect size $Zr$ (or predicted value, $y_i$), we calculated the absolute deviance between the results of each individual analysis and the meta-analytic mean. We performed a Box-Cox transformation to ensure that the resulting values followed a normal distribution. We used a Gaussian GLM with an identity link function. Reviewer rating was included as a fixed effect in the model (either as a continuous or categorical variable). Each analysis has been rated by multiple peer reviewers, so for each reviewer score to be included, each deviation score is included in the analysis multiple times. To account for the non-independence of multiple ratings of the same analysis, we planned to include analysis identity as a random effect in our GLMM. In addition, to account for potential differences among reviewers in their scoring of analyses, we planned to include reviewer identity as a random effect. We conducted a similar analysis for continuous versus categorical quality ratings and for each of the four responses ($Zr$, $y_{25}$, $y_{50}$, $y_{75}$) for both Blue Tit and Eucalyptus datasets.

The model was specified as follows: $$ DeviationScore_{j} = Box-Cox(abs(DeviationFromMean_{j}))$$ $$DeviationScore_{ij} \sim Rating_{ij} + ReviewerIdentity_{i} + AnalysisIdentity_{j}$$ $$ReviewerIdentity_i \sim Normal(0,\sigma^2)$$ $$AnalysisIdentity_j \sim Normal(0,\sigma^2)$$

Where $DeviationFromMean_{ij}$ is the deviation from the meta-analytic mean for the *j*th analysis, by the *i*th reviewer, $ReviewerIdentity_{i}$ is the random intercept for assigned to each *i* reviewer, and $AnalysisIdentity_{j}$ is the random intercept for assigned to each *j* analysis, both of which are assumed to be normally distributed with a mean of 0 and a variance of $\sigma^2$.

::: boxBorder
**Preregistration deviation:**

We intended to include random effects of both analysis identity and reviewer identity in the model but our dataset was sparse, with reviewers reviewing a small number of analyses and the models failed to converge. Removing one of the random effects was necessary to ensure that the models converged. The models that included the categorical quality rating converged when including Reviewer ID, the models that included the continuous quality rating converged when including Analysis ID.

Further, in the original analysis plan we intended to do this for reviewers' initial and revised ratings but we did not collect data for these separately so we only model peoples' final ratings (which may or may not have been updated).
:::

*Deviation Scores as explained by the uniqueness of variables in each analysis*

The next set of univariate analyses aim to explain deviations from the mean effects based on a measure of the uniqueness of the set of variables included in each analysis. We used Sorensen's Similarity Index as a measure of 'uniqueness.' Sorensen's Similarity Index is an index typically used to compare species composition across sites, but in this case we treat variables as species and individual analyses as sites. We calculate an individual Sorensen's Similarity Index value for each analysis by calculating the pairwise Sorensen's value for all pairs of analyses (of the same dataset), and then taking the average across these Sorensen's values for each analysis. We will calculate the Sorensen's index values using the *betapart* R package (Baselga et al. 2018):

$$
\beta_{Sorensen} = \frac{b+c}{2a+b+c}
$$ where $a$ is the number of variables common to both analyses, $b$ is the number of variables that occur in the first analysis but not in the second and $c$ is the number of variables that occur in the second analysis.

We used the per-model average Sorensen's index value as an independent variable to predict the deviation score in a normally distributed general linear model, using an identity link, with no random effect since each analysis is included only once, in the *stats* package in R (R_Core_Team 2019):

$$ DeviationScore_{j} \sim \beta Sorensen_{j}$$

*Deviation Scores as explained by the inclusion of random effects*

Next, we assessed the relationship between the inclusion of random effects in analyses and the deviation from the mean effect size in the *lmer* package in R (R_Core_Team 2019). Our threshold for implementing this model was that there were at least 5 analyses that do and 5 analyses that do not include random effects. We manually coded a binary predictor variable for each analysis, specifying whether it included random effects and included this as a fixed effect in our set of univariate analyses.

$$ DeviationScore_{j} \sim RandomEffects_{j}$$

*Multivariate Analysis*

In our final pre-registered analysis we conducted a multivariate analysis with the predictors described above: continuous peer-review ratings '0-100' peer-review ratings of publishabiltiy (1-4); Sorensen's index, presence/absence of random effects (if sample size is sufficient). We included random effects of analysis identity and reviewer identity, as for the model of reviewer rating described above, fitted using the *lme4* package in R:

$$ DeviationScore_{j} \sim RatingContinuous_{ij} + RatingCategorical_{ij} + βSorensen_{j} + AnalysisIdentity_{j} + ReviewerIdentity_{i} $$

::: boxBorder
**Preregistration Deviation:**

We pre-registered including participants original and revised continuous and categorical ratings in this analysis but in the way we collected data, revised ratings overwrote original ratings. Therefore, we have only included reviewers final ratings which may represent revised ratings for a subset of reviewers.
:::

### Model Fit and Performance Statistics

All fitted models were evaluated using the `performance()` function from the [@Ludecke2021] package.

List statistics we calculated: - R2 - what else?

For GLMMs `performance()` calculates the marginal and conditional $R^2$ values as well as the contribution of random effects (ICC), based on Nakagawa et al. (2017). The conditional $R^2$ accounts for both the fixed and random effects, while the marginal $R^2$ considers only the variance of the fixed effects. The contribution of random effects is given by subtracting the marginal $R^2$ from the conditional $R^2$.

### Post-hoc Exploratory Analyses

We conducted all the analyses described above for each of the four responses (Zr, y25th, ymedian, y75th), for each of the datasets (Eucalyptus and Blue Tit), as pre-registered. We also explored the effect of removing outliers from these analyses. We trialed removing analyses that 1) recieved at least one rating of "Deeply Flawed and Unpublishable", 2) received at least one rating of either "Deeply Flawed and Unpublishable" or "Publishable with Major Revisions", and 3) removing the top outlier for out of sample prediction analyses and top 2 and bottom 2 outliers for Zr analyses for both datasets.

### Data-exclusion

We pre-registered a series of a priori rules for excluding analyses from our synthesis. We excluded:

-   Any individual analysis submitted after we have completed peer review or those unaccompanied by analysis files that allow us to understand what the analysts did.

-   Any individual analysis that does not produce an outcome that can be interpreted as an answer to our primary question (as posed above) for the respective data set. For instance, in the case of the data on blue tit chick growth, we would exclude any analysis that does not include something that can be interpreted as growth or size as a dependent (response) variable, and in the case of the Eucalyptus establishment data, we would exclude any analysis that does not include a measure of grass cover among the independent (predictor) variables.

-   Also, as described above, any analysis that cannot produce an effect that can be converted to a signed Zr will be excluded from analyses of Zr.

## Summary Statistics

In total, 146 analyst teams, comprising 206 analysts, contributed analyses of the two datasets examined in this study. Many of these analysis teams contributed multiple analyses of a single dataset, some analysed both datasets. In total, the Blue Tit data was analysed by 79 teams of analysts who performed 174 distinct analyses, the eucalypt dataset was analysed by 68 teams who performed 128 distinct analyses. Due to the data requirements for the formal evaluations of variation between analyses, we were only able to include subsets of analyses in the evaluations of variation in effect size, and in model predictions (see Table \@ref(tab:Table1) for break down of how many analyses were included in each subset). Models of the Blue Tit dataset were usually normally distributed, mixed effects models (Table \@ref(tab:Table1)). Models of the Eucalypt dataset were typically non-normally distributed mixed effects models.

The composition of models varied substantially (Table \@ref(tab:Table2)) in regards to the number of fixed and random effects, interaction terms and the number of data points used. For the Blue Tit dataset, models used up to 19 fixed effects, 12 random effects, and 10 interaction terms and had sample sizes ranging from 76 to 3720 For the Eucalypt dataset models had up to 31 fixed effects, 4 random effects, 26 interaction terms and sample sizes ranging from 18 to 351.


::: {.cell warning.hidden='true' message.hidden='true'}

```{.r .cell-code .hidden}
#table 2 - summary of mean, sd and range in number of different types of variables used
Table2 %>% 
  rename(SD = sd) %>%   
  group_by(variable) %>% 
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = dataset,
    names_sep = ".",
    values_from = c(mean, SD, min, max)
  ) %>% 
  gt::gt(caption = gt::md("Mean, standard deviation and range of number of fixed and random variables and interaction terms used in models and sample size used. Repeated for Effect Size analyses only ($Z_r$), out-of-sample prediction only ($y_i$), and all analyses combined."), 
         rowname_col = "subset") %>% 
 gt::tab_spanner_delim(delim = ".") %>% 
    gt::fmt_scientific(columns = c(contains("mean"), contains("SD")),
                     decimals = 2) %>% 
   gt::cols_label_with(fn = Hmisc::capitalize) %>% 
    tab_style(
    style = cell_text(transform = "capitalize"),
    locations = cells_column_spanners()
  ) %>% 
   gt::cols_label_with(c(contains("Eucalyptus")), 
                       fn = ~ gt::md(paste0("*",.x, "*"))) %>% 
    gt::sub_values(columns = subset, values = c("effects"), 
                 replacement = gt::md("$$Z_r$$")) %>% 
   gt::sub_values(columns = subset, values = c("predictions"), 
                  replacement = gt::md("$$y_i$$")) %>% 
     gt::sub_values(columns = subset, values = c("all"), 
                  replacement = gt::md("All analyses")) %>% 
  gt::opt_stylize(style = 6, color = "gray")%>% 
  gt::as_raw_html()
```

The choice of variables also differed substantially between models (Table \@ref(tab:Table3)). Considering all submitted analyses, the Blue Tit dataset had 52 candidate variables, which were used in a mean of 26.13 analyses (range 0- 120), the eucalyptus dataset had 58 candidate variables which were used in a mean of 9.07 analyses (range 0-55).


::: {.cell warning.hidden='true' message.hidden='true'}

```{.r .cell-code .hidden}
#table 3 - summary of mean, sd and range for the number of analyses in which each variable was used
Table3 %>% 
  rename(SD = sd) %>% 
  pivot_wider(
    names_from = dataset,
    names_sep = ".",
    values_from = c(mean, SD, min, max)
  ) %>% 
  ungroup %>% 
  gt::gt(caption = gt::md("Mean, SD, minimum and maximum number of analyses in which each variable was used, for effect size analyses only ($Z_r$), out-of-sample prediction only ($y_i$), and all analyses combined."),
         rowname_col = "subset") %>% 
    gt::tab_spanner_delim(delim = ".") %>% 
    gt::fmt_scientific(columns = c(contains("mean"), contains("SD")),
                     decimals = 2) %>% 
   gt::cols_label_with(fn = Hmisc::capitalize) %>% 
   gt::cols_label_with(c(contains("Eucalyptus")), fn = ~ gt::md(paste0("*",.x, "*"))) %>% 
    gt::sub_values(columns = subset, values = c("effects"), 
                 replacement = gt::md("$$Z_r$$")) %>% 
   gt::sub_values(columns = subset, values = c("predictions"), 
                  replacement = gt::md("$$y_i$$")) %>% 
     gt::sub_values(columns = subset, values = c("all"), 
                  replacement = gt::md("All analyses")) %>% 
  gt::opt_stylize(style = 6, color = "gray") %>% 
      tab_style(
    style = cell_text(transform = "capitalize"),
    locations = cells_column_spanners()
  ) %>% 
  gt::as_raw_html()
```

Analysts provided qualitative descriptions of the conclusions of their analyses. Each analysis team provided one conclusion per dataset. These conclusions took into account the results of multiple formal analyses as well exploratory and visual analysis of the data. We classified these conclusions into: (Table \@ref(tab:Table4)):

-   Mixed: some evidence supporting a positive effect, some evidence supporting a negative effect
-   Conclusive negative: negative relationship described without caveat
-   Qualified negative: negative relationship but only in certain circumstances or where analysts express uncertainty in their result
-   Conclusive none: analysts interpret the results as conclusive of no effect
-   None qualified: analysts found no evidence of a relationship but they describe the potential for an undetected effect
-   Qualified positive: positive relationship but only in certain circumstances or where analysts express uncertainty in their result
-   Conclusive negative: positive relationship described without caveat

For the Blue Tit dataset, most analysts found a negative relationship between chick growth and sibling competition, though there was a spread between analysts finding no effect, mixed effects or negative effects. For the Eucalypt dataset, there was a broader spread of conclusions with at least one analyst team providing conclusions consistent with each conclusion category. The most common conclusion for the eucalypt dataset was that there was no relationship between grass cover and eucalypt recruitment (either conclusive or qualified description of no relationship).

```{.r .cell-code .hidden}
plot_forest <- function(data, intercept = TRUE, MA_mean = TRUE){
  if(MA_mean == FALSE){
    data <- filter(data, Parameter != "overall")
  }
  
    p <- ggplot(data, aes(y = estimate, 
                        x =  Parameter, 
                        ymin = conf.low, 
                        ymax = conf.high,
                        shape = point_shape,
                        colour = parameter_type)) +
    geom_pointrange() +
    ggforestplot::theme_forest() +
    theme(axis.line = element_line(linewidth = 0.10, colour = "black"),
          axis.line.y = element_blank(),
          text = element_text(family = "Helvetica"),
          axis.text.y = element_blank()) +
    guides(shape = "none", colour = "none") +
    coord_flip() +
    labs(y = "Standardised Effect Size, Zr",
         x = element_blank()) +
    scale_y_continuous(breaks = c(-4,-3,-2,-1,0,1),
                       minor_breaks = seq(from = -4.5, to = 1.5, by = 0.5)) +
    NatParksPalettes::scale_color_natparks_d("Glacier")
    
    if(intercept == TRUE){
      p <- p + geom_hline(yintercept = 0)
    }
    if(MA_mean == TRUE){
      p <- p + geom_hline(aes(yintercept = meta_analytic_mean), 
                          data = data,
                          colour = "#01353D", 
                          linetype = "dashed")
    }
    
  return(p)
}
```

![Forest plots of meta-analytic estimated standardized effect-sizes (blue circles) and their 95% confidence intervals are displayed for each analysis included in the meta-analysis model. The meta-analytic mean effect-size is denoted by a black triangle, with error bars also representing the 95% confidence interval. The dashed black line demarcates effect sizes of 0, whereby no effect of the test variable on the response variable is found.  **A.** Blue Tit analyses:  Points where $Zr$ and its associated confidence intervals are less than 0 indicate analyses that found a negative effect of sibling number on nestling growth. Points that have confidence intervals crossing 0 indicate no relationship between the test and response variable. Points where $Zr$ and its associated confidence interval are greater than 0 indicate the analyses found a positive effect of sibling number on nestling growth. **B.** *Eucalyptus* analyses: Blue points where Zr and its associated confidence intervals are greater than 0 indicate analyses that found a positive relationship of grass cover on *Eucalyptus* seedling success. Points that have confidence intervals crossing 0 indicate no relationship between the test and response variable. Points where $Zr$ and associated confidence intervals are less than 0 indicate that the analysis found a negative relationship between grass cover and *Eucalyptus* seedling success.](ms_results_files/figure-html/forest-plots-Zr-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


Although the majority (ninety-two) of analyses of the blue tit dataset found nestling growth decreases with sibling competition, there is variability in the direction of effects, with thirty-six finding no effect of sibling competition on nestling growth (Confidence Interval overlapping with zero), and 3 finding a positive effect of sibling competition on nestling growth (Figure \@ref(fig:forest-plots-Zr)A). There was substantial variation in the magnitude of effects, with standardised correlation coefficients uniformly ranging from -1.55 and 0.38, and the meta-analytic mean being -0.35 $\pm$ 0.06 (Figure \@ref(fig:forest-plots-Zr)A and Table \@ref(tab:effects-params)).

Meta-analysis of the Eucalyptus dataset shows substantial variability in the direction of effects, with the majority fifty-three of analysts finding no effect of grass cover on eucalyptus seedling success, approximately a quarter (fifteen) finding a negative effect of grass cover on seedling success, and eleven finding a positive effect of grass cover on seedling success (Figure \@ref(fig:forest-plots-Zr)B).

Effect sizes tended to be much smaller for the Eucalyptus dataset, with a meta-analytic mean effect size of -0.09 $\pm$ 0.12 (Table \@ref(tab:effects-params)). However there is huge variability in the magnitude of effect sizes, varying from -4.47 to 0.39. With several strongly positive outliers (Figure \@ref(fig:forest-plots-Zr)B).

### Quantifying heterogeneity

The statistic $I^2$ quantifies the proportion of heterogeneity driven by between-analysis variance versus heterogeneity driven by within-analysis variance, or sampling error. Total $I^2$ for the evolutionary biology analyses was extremely large, at 97.73$\%$, showing that nearly all heterogeneity is driven predominantly by between-study variation, or analytic heterogeneity, with only 2.27$\%$ of the total heterogeneity caused by sampling error (Table \@ref(tab:tbl-effects-heterogeneity)). Similarly, for the ecology dataset, the between-study heterogeneity variance was estimated at 98.59$\%$.

Although the overall heterogeneity statistics were approximately similar for both Eucalyptus and Blue tit datasets, the relative composition of that heterogeneity differed. For both datasets, the majority of heterogeneity was driven by between-`study_id` differences, as opposed to between-`team_id` differences, with 40.11$\%$ and 57.63$\%$ apportioned to between-`team_id` and between-`study_id` differences, respectively (Table \@ref(tab:tbl-effects-heterogeneity)).

However, for the ecology dataset, nearly all of the total heterogeneity was driven by differences between analyses as opposed to differences between teams, with 6.88$\%$ and 91.71$\%$ apportioned to between-`team_id` and between-`study_id` differences, respectively (Table \@ref(tab:tbl-effects-heterogeneity)).

```{.r .cell-code .hidden}
                            estimate_type == "Zr", 
                            model_name == "MA_mod",
                            publishable_subset == "All"))  %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  select(dataset, 
         publishable_subset, 
         exclusion_set,
         estimate_type,
         mod_fit_stats,
         MA_fit_stats) %>% 
  unnest(cols = c(mod_fit_stats,
         MA_fit_stats)) %>% 
  group_by(dataset, 
           estimate_type, 
           exclusion_set,
           publishable_subset) %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols = -c(dataset, 
                         estimate_type, 
                         exclusion_set,
                         publishable_subset)) %>% 
  mutate(publishable_subset = 
           case_when(publishable_subset == "All" ~ 
                       "All analyses",
                     publishable_subset == "data_flawed" ~ 
                       "Analyses receiving at least one 'Unpublishable' rating removed",
                     publishable_subset == "data_flawed_major" ~ 
                       "Analyses receiving at least one 'Unpublishable' and or 'Major Revisions' rating removed",
                     TRUE ~ ""),
         exclusion_set = 
           case_when(exclusion_set == "complete" ~ "No",
                     TRUE ~ "Yes")) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = name) %>% 
  ungroup %>% 
  select(-estimate_type, -AIC, -BIC, -TAU2, -contains("Omnibus")) %>% 
  mutate(exclusion_set = case_when(exclusion_set == "Yes" ~ ", Outliers Removed",
                                   exclusion_set == "No" ~ "",
                                   TRUE ~ exclusion_set)) %>% 
  unite("data_subset", publishable_subset, exclusion_set, sep = "", remove = TRUE) %>% 
  group_by(data_subset) %>% 
  arrange(data_subset) %>% 
  gt::gt(caption = gt::md("Heterogeneity in the estimated effects and other variance components for meta-analyses fit to full dataset with conservative exclusions, and to the same dataset with outliers removed. ${\\tau}_{1}^{2}$ corresponds to the variance for random effect `TeamIdentifier` and  ${\\tau}_{2}^{2}$ corresponds to the variance for the random effect `study_id`, nested under `TeamIdentifier`. ${N}_{Obs}$ is the number of total observations in the fitted model. ${I^2}_{Total}$ is the total heterogeneity not attributable to sampling error, ${I^2}_{TeamIdentifier}$ is the heterogeneity due to differences between `TeamIdentifier` and ${I^2}_{TeamIdentifier}$ is the heterogeneity attributable to between-`study_id` differences.   gt::fmt_percent(columns = "I2_Total", scale_values = FALSE, decimals = 3) %>%
```

#### Post-hoc Analysis: Exploring outlier characteristics and the effect of removal on heterogeneity

For the analyses of the eucalyptus dataset, all negative outliers were based on extremely small subsets of the analysis dataset and in one case, extreme aggregation of the dataset. One analysis (analysis X) was based on only 18 observations after aggregating across the 18 sites in the analysis dataset. The other extremely large outliers had sample sizes that were less than half of the mean sample size across the entire set of analyses (n = X, Y, Z, out of a total N analyses).

Surprisingly, for the Blue Tit analyses, both the largest and smallest effect sizes in the blue tit analyses (Figure \@ref(fig:forest-plots-Zr)A) come from the same analyst (insert analysis IDs), with identical models in covariate structure, but for the response variable. Switching out the response variable (from X to Y) but retaining the same predictors and random effects structure resulted in a wild reversing of the direction of effect, and change in the magnitude of the effect (from X to Y). Three of the variables used in these two analyses are highly correlated predictor variables, in particular brood size at the start of the nestling period, and brood size at day 14 of nestling period, with a correlation of over 0.9 (ref. to correlation plot included in recent presentations, insert into supp. mat.).

> So in the case of the positively signed outlier, this created an unexpected direction of effect, since presumably the focal variable was explaining only some residual variation, while in the case of the negatively signed outlier, the direction of effect seemed logical, but the value was extreme, probably because the highly correlated predictor (X) was explaining some of the residual variance and making the primary effect appear stronger. **SHIFT TO DISCUSSION?**

When the outliers are dropped from the eucalyptus analyses, $I^2$ decreases substantially from a high degree of heterogeneity (98.59%) using Higgins [-@higgins2003] suggested benchmarks for all analyses, to a medium degree (66.19%, Table \@ref(tab:tbl-effects-heterogeneity)). Conversely, dropping outlier analyses of the blue tit dataset, did not substantially reduce the the proportion of heterogeneity driven by between-study variation, $I^2$ (Table \@ref(tab:tbl-effects-heterogeneity)), signifying that variation in effect sizes is driven much less by analytic variation than sampling error for analyses of the eucalyptus dataset than for analyses of the blue tit dataset.

#### Post-hoc analysis: Exploring the effect of removing analyses with poor peer-review ratings on heterogeneity

There is virtually no impact of removing poorly rated analyses on the meta-analytic mean. For the Eucalyptus dataset the meta-analytic mean shifts from 0.03 ro 0.02 when analyses rated as unpublishable are removed, and to 0.04 when both unpublishable and analyses requiring major revisions are removed and the confidence intervals for these estimates are overlapping (Table \@ref(tab:effects-params)). A similar pattern is seen for the blue tit dataset where there are minute shifts in the meta-analytic mean, and confidence intervals of all three estimates are overlapping so there is no significant difference in any shifts due to removing analyses with poor peer-review ratings (Table \@ref(tab:effects-params)). Refitting the meta-analysis with with a fixed effect for categorical rating also demonstrates no differences in group meta-analytic means due to peer-review ratings (Figure S\@ref(fig:euc-cat-ratings-MA)).

For the blue tit dataset there are negligible changes in $I^2_{Total}$, however for the eucalyptus dataset, removing analyses with unpublishable ratings strongly reduced the overall heterogeneity from $I^2_{Total} = 98.59\%$ to $I^2_{Total} = 66.19\%$ while removing analyses receiving either ratings of 'unpublishable' or needing 'major revisions' reduced the total heterogeneity to $I^2_{Total} = 88.92\%$ (Table \@ref(tab:tbl-effects-heterogeneity)). The distribution of heterogeneity across groups did change, however, for the meta-analysis where only the majority of heterogeneity shifted from mostly between individual analyse ($I^2_{TeamIdentifier,study\_id} = 91.71\%$ ) to wholly between Teams $I^2_{TeamIdentifier} = 88.91\%$ when analyses rated as 'unpublishable' or 'needing major revisions' are excluded (Table \@ref(tab:tbl-effects-heterogeneity)). The pattern of having the majority of heterogeneity driven by between analysis differences remained for the meta-analysis when only unpublishable-rated analyses were removed, however, much more heterogeneity was driven by between-Team differences (6.88% versus. 28.32%, Table \@ref(tab:tbl-effects-heterogeneity)).

#### Post-hoc analysis: Exploring the effect of different exclusion rules on heterogeneity

We created two different sets of data with different degrees of conservatism in our exclusion coded, the first dataset excluded analyses according to our preregistered exclusion rules, while the second dataset was generated with more stringent exclusion rules after manually checking the submitted results of all analyses (Table S\@ref(tab:tbl-Zr-exclusion-subsetting). Different degrees of conservatism in excluding analyses had minimal impact on the meta-analytic mean for both blue tit and eucalyptus analyses, regardless of whether outliers were excluded (Table S\@ref(tab:tbl-Zr-exclusion-subsetting). However, applying conservative and additioanl exclusions to the blue tit analyses did shift the amount of total heterogeneity apportioned among between-`TeamIdentifier` differences and between-`study_id` differences, a greater amount of heterogeneity being driven by between-`TeamIdentifier` differences ( $I^2_{TeamIdentifier} =$ 40.11%, $I^2_{TeamIdentifier,study\_id} =$ 57.63% under conservative exclusions, $I^2_{TeamIdentifier} =$ 38.42%, $I^2_{TeamIdentifier,study\_id} =$ 59.35% under further exclusions, Table S\@ref(tab:tbl-Zr-exclusion-subsetting)).

### Explaining Variation in Deviation Scores

None of the preregistered predictors of deviation scores explained variation in deviation scores.

We obtained reviews from 128 reviewers who provided a mean of 3.27 (range 1 - 11). Analyses of the Blue Tit dataset recieved a total of 240 reviews, each was reviewed by a mean of 3.87(sd 0.71, range 3-5). Analyses of the Eucalyptus dataset received a total of 178 reviews, each was reviews by a mean of 4.24(sd 0.79, range 3-6). We tested for inter rater reliability to examine how similarly reviewers reviewed each analysis and found little agreement between reviewers, when considering the

Many of the models of deviance as a function of peer-review ratings faced issues of failure to converge or singularity issues due to very sparse design matrices with our pre-registered random effects (study id and reviewer ID) (See [this stack exchange issue for details and what to include in supp matt analysis](https://stats.stackexchange.com/questions/76488/error-system-is-computationally-singular-when-running-a-glm).These issues persisted after increasing the tolerance and changing the optimizer (See supp. matt. secion X). For both Eucalyptus and Blue tit datasets models with continuous ratings as a predictor were singular when both pre-registered random effects were included. We first dropped the Reviewer response ID random effect, as we thought `study_id` was a more important driver of variation in deviation scores than reviewer ID. To aid inference of model results given this important structuring variable was dropped, we performed an analysis looking at the inter-rater reliability ratings of each of the reviewers. Unfortunately for the models of deviance from the meta-analytic mean as a function of the categorical ratings, dropping the reviewer ID as a random effect meant that models would not converge. Alternately for these models we retained Reviewer ID as a random effect, and dropped study ID as a random effect.

*Coefs and interpretation*

We re-ran the multi-level meta-analysis with a fixed-effect for the categorical publishability ratings and found no difference in mean standardised effect sizes among publishability ratings \@ref(fig:euc-cat-ratings-MA).

**Model FIt Summary Statistics**

For each model the marginal and conditional coefficient of determination (${R}_{M}^2$, ${R}_{C}^2$) is reported in table \@ref(tab:model-summary-stats-ratings-cont), as well as the intra-class correlation coefficient (ICC), root mean squared error (RMSE), and the residual standard deviation.

For models of deviation scores as a function of *continuous* peer-review ratings of both datasets showed the same pattern, where in both instances the marginal $R^2$ is substantially lower than the conditional or total $R^2$ for the overall model (Table \@ref(tab:model-summary-stats-ratings-cont)), with the conditional coefficient of determination ${R}_{C}^2$ being equal to or near 1, signifying that most of the unexplained variation is between groups (reviewers rather than among deviation scores of analyses rated by a given reviewer). While the marginal coefficient of determination ${R}_{M}^2$ was extremely small and approaching 0 in both instances, indicating that continuous peer-ratings do not explain much variation in deviation scores.

${R}_{M}^2$ for models of deviation scores predicted by *categorical* peer-review ratings were also close to 0, however for these models ${R}_{C}^2$ was conversely very small (though not approaching 0) instead of approaching or being equal to 1. This pattern indicates that continuous peer-review ratings explain very little variation in deviation scores, most of that unexplained variation between observations is within groups (reviewers) rather than between groups (reviewers).

ICC ranges from 0 - 1 indexing how strongly observations in the same group resemble each other, and can be interpreted as "the proportion of the variance explained by the grouping structure in the population" [@Ludecke2021]. An ICC of - indicate that the grouping is not informative and there is no correlation between observations, and 1, if all observations in the group are equal [@gelman2007].

For both datasets, models of deviation from the meta-analytic mean with *continuous* peer-review ratings as a predictor, the ICC is at or near 1, indicating that deviation from the meta-analytic mean for analyses rated by the same reviewer are highly correlated and that the random-effect structure specification is meaningful (Table \@\@ref(tab:model-summary-stats-ratings-cont)). However, for both datasets models of deviation from the meta-analytic mean with *categorical* peer-review ratings as a predictor, ICC was very small or close to 0 (Table \@ref(tab:model-summary-stats-ratings-cont)), showing that categorical peer-review ratings were uncorrelated within individual analyses.

The RMSE is the square root of the variance of the residuals measures the absolute fit of the model to the data (difference between observed data to model's fitted values). It is in the same units as the response variable (Box-Cox transformed absolute deviation from the analytic mean) and can be interpreted as the standard deviation of the unexplained variance, such that lower values indicate greater model fit [@Ludecke2020].

For both datasets, models of deviation scores with continuous ratings as the fixed-effect term had lower RMSE than for models with categorical ratings as the fixed-term effect, indicating better model fit (less residual variance) with the continuous predictor as opposed to categorical peer-review ratings as the predictor (Table \@ref(tab:model-summary-stats-ratings-cont)). ManyEcoEvo_viz %>% 
```{.r .cell-code .hidden}
  filter(exclusion_set == "complete", 
         publishable_subset == "All", 
         model_name %in% c("box_cox_rating_cont", "box_cox_rating_cat")) %>% 
  mutate(perf = map(model, performance::performance),
         mod_sum_stats = map(model, broom.mixed::glance)) %>% 
  hoist(perf, "R2_conditional", "R2_marginal", "ICC", "Sigma", "RMSE") %>% 
  hoist(mod_sum_stats, "nobs") %>% 
  select(-model, 
         -mod_summary, 
         -tidy_mod_summary, 
         -MA_fit_stats, 
         -mod_fit_stats, 
         -ends_with("plot"), 
         -perf, 
         -mod_sum_stats, 
         -estimate_type, 
         -publishable_subset, 
         -exclusion_set) %>% 
  bind_rows({
    ManyEcoEvo_viz %>% 
     filter(exclusion_set == "complete", 
            publishable_subset == "All", 
            model_name %in% c("sorensen_glm", "uni_mixed_effects")) %>% 
     mutate(perf = map(model, performance::performance),
            mod_sum_stats = map(model, broom.mixed::glance)) %>% 
  select(dataset, model_name, perf, mod_sum_stats) %>% 
  hoist(mod_sum_stats, "nobs") %>% 
  hoist(perf, "R2", "RMSE", "Sigma") %>% 
  select(-perf, -mod_sum_stats)
  }) %>% 
  group_by(model_name) %>% 
  relocate("R2", .before = starts_with("R2_")) %>% 
  gt::gt(caption = gt::md("Model summary metrics for models of deviation as a function of both categorical and continuous peer-review ratings for blue tit and eucalyptus analyses. Coefficient of determination, $R^2$, is reported for models of deviation as a function of Sorensen diversity scores and presence of random effects, while $R^{2}_{Conditional}$, $R^{2}_{Marginal}$ and the intra-class correlation (ICC) are reported for models of deviation as explained by peer-review ratings. For all models the residual standard deviation $\\sigma$, root mean squared error (RMSE) were calculated. The number of observations ($N_{Obs.}$) is displayed for reference.")) %>% 
  gt::opt_stylize(style = 6, color = "gray") %>% 
  gt::sub_missing(missing_text = "") %>% 
  gt::fmt(columns = function(x) rlang::is_bare_numeric(x),
          fns = function(x) format(x, digits = 3)) %>% 
  gt::cols_label(dataset = "Dataset",
                 R2 = gt::md("$$R^2$$"),
                 R2_conditional = gt::md("$$R^{2}_{Conditional}$$"),
                 R2_marginal = gt::md("$$R^{2}_{Marginal}$$"),
                 Sigma = gt::md("$$\\sigma$$"),
                 nobs = gt::md("$$N_{Obs.}$$"))
```

-   Very small negative effect of numeric peer-rating on deviation, (double 100 represents, I suspect beta.part implements this as *dissimilarity* index) BUT this result is HIGHLY sensitive to outlier inclusion, with the slope reversing direction when outliers are excluded (supplementary material):
    -   Study-id R_2EAXdnsMi6ugMYh-2-2-1 seems to down-weight the effect of increasing rating on deviation from meta-analytic mean for the blue tit analyses. When excluded negative effect of increasing diversity index on deviation.
    -   Opposite effect observed in Eucalyptus dataset - outliers increasing effect of lower diversity index on deviation. When outliers excluded, slope switches to slightly negative value.

```{.r .cell-code .hidden}
plot_model_means_box_cox_cat <- function(dat, 
                                         variable, 
                                         predictor_means, 
                                         new_order, 
                                         title, 
                                         back_transform = FALSE) {
  dat <- mutate(dat, 
                "{{variable}}" := # 
                  fct_relevel(.f = {{variable}}, 
                              new_order)
  )
  
  if(back_transform == TRUE){
    dat <- dat %>% 
      mutate(box_cox_abs_deviation_score_estimate = 
               sae::bxcx(unique(dat$lambda),
                         x = box_cox_abs_deviation_score_estimate, InverseQ = TRUE))
    
    predictor_means <- predictor_means %>% 
      as_tibble() %>% 
      mutate(lambda = dat$lambda %>% unique()) %>%  
      mutate(across(.cols = -PublishableAsIs,
              ~ sae::bxcx(unique(dat$lambda),x = .x, InverseQ = TRUE)))
  }
  
  p <- ggplot(dat, aes(x = {{variable}},
                        y = box_cox_abs_deviation_score_estimate)) +
    # Add base dat
    geom_violin(aes(fill = {{variable}}),
                trim = TRUE, 
                # scale = "count", #TODO consider toggle on/off?
                colour = "white") +
    see::geom_jitter2(width = 0.05, alpha = 0.5) +
    # Add pointrange and line from means
    geom_line(dat = predictor_means, aes(y = Mean, group = 1), linewidth = 1) +
    geom_pointrange(
      dat = predictor_means,
      aes(y = Mean, ymin = CI_low, ymax = CI_high),
      size = 1,
      color = "grey",
      alpha = 0.5
    ) +
    # Improve colors
    see::scale_fill_material_d(discrete = TRUE, 
                               name = "",
                               palette = "rainbow",
                               labels = pull(dat, {{variable}}) %>% 
                                 levels() %>% 
                                 capwords(),
                               reverse = TRUE) +
    EnvStats::stat_n_text() +
    see::theme_modern() +
    theme(axis.text.x=element_blank()) +
    ggtitle(label = title)
  
  if(back_transform == TRUE){
    p <- p + 
      labs(x = "Categorical Peer Review Rating", 
         y = "Absolute Deviation from\n Meta-Anaytic Mean Zr") 
  } else {
    p <- p + labs(x = "Categorical Peer Review Rating", 
         y = "Box Cox Transformed \n Absolute Deviation from\n Meta-Analytic Mean Zr") 
  }
  
  return(p)
}
```

#### Deviation Scores as explained by the uniqueness of variables in each analysis

We use Sorensen diversity indices to calculate the uniqueness of the set of predictor variables used in each model. Analyses of the influence of uniqueness of variables on deviation in effect sizes of the Blue Tit dataset have a mean Sorensen score of 0.59 (range 0.43-0.86), analyses of the Eucalypt dataset have a mean Sorensen score of 0.69 (range 0.55-0.98).

Uniqueness of predictor variables is a poor predictor of how different any given model will be from the meta-analytic mean. The confidence intervals for the effect of uniqueness overlap 0 for both blue tit (mean 0.23, 95% CI -1,1.46 and Eucalyptus analyses (mean 0.29, 95% CI -2.74,3.32.

#### Deviation Scores as explained by the inclusion of random effects

There were only 3 analyses that did not include random effects in their model, which is below the pre-registered threshold for fitting a model of the box-cox transformed deviation from the meta-analytic mean as a function of whether the analysis included random-effects or not. Consequently we performed this analysis for the *Eucalyptus* dataset only. There was no effect of random-effect inclusion on deviation from meta-analytic mean.

```{.r .cell-code .hidden}
plot_model_means_RE <- function(data, variable, predictor_means) {
  p <- ggplot(data, aes(x = as.factor({{variable}}), 
              y = box_cox_abs_deviation_score_estimate)) +
  # Add base data
  geom_violin(aes(fill = as.factor({{variable}})), color = "white") +
  see::geom_jitter2(width = 0.05, alpha = 0.5) +
  # Add pointrange and line from means
  geom_line(data = predictor_means, aes(y = Mean, group = 1), size = 1) +
  geom_pointrange(
    data = predictor_means,
    aes(y = Mean, ymin = CI_low, ymax = CI_high),
    size = 1,
    color = "white"
  ) +
  # Improve colors
  see::scale_fill_material(palette = "ice",
                           discrete = TRUE, 
                           labels = c("No Random Effects", "Random effects"), 
                           name = "") +
  see::theme_modern() +
    EnvStats::stat_n_text() +
  labs(x = "Random Effects Included", 
       y = "Box Cox Transformed \n Absolute Deviation Score")
  return(p)
}
```

:::


The multivariate models do a poor job of explaining how different from the meta-analytic mean each analysis would be. For the blue tit analyses the R2 value for the whole model is 0.11, and for the fixed effects component is 0.01, the residual standard deviation for the model is 0.66. For the multivariate analysis of the Eucalyptus analyses had an R2 for the whole model of 0.11, and for the fixed effects component is 0.03, the residual standard deviation for the model is 1.09.

In the blue tit multivariate model, all of the fixed effects have 95% confidence intervals that overlap 0, so we cant conclude that continuous review rating, categorical review rating or uniqueness of variables included had any effect on how different any given analysis is from the meta-analytic mean. The pattern is largely similar for the Eucalptus analyses, where confidence intervals for fixed effects for continuous reviewer rating, and uniqueness of variable selection overlapped 0. However, when it comes to the fixed effects for categorical reviewer ratings, it appears that analyses that were reviewed to be 'publishable as is' and 'publishable with major revisions' may produce results more different to the meta-analytic mean than those that were in the reference class of 'deeply flawed and unpublishable'.However, the estimates are very uncertain (Eucalyptus fixed effect for 'publishable as is' 1.14 (95% CI 0.01,2.27), and for 'publishable with major revision' 0.86 (95% CI 0.07,1.64).
